Part 0 — The Ground

Before any structure can be built, the ground must be laid. Part 0 establishes the foundational axioms that cannot be proven from within the system but must be accepted as the starting points of all mathematical reasoning. It also introduces the concept of infinity, the first and most profound idea that lifts mathematics beyond the finite.

---

Chapter 0 — The Axiomatic Seal: The 10 Pillars of Certainty

These are the self‑evident truths that cannot be proven from within the system but must be accepted to allow the entire edifice of human civilization to stand. Without them, the mathematics in the following chapters has no ground upon which to rest.

---

I. The Logical Foundations (Aristotelian / Fregean)

· Law of Identity:
    A = A
  
    A thing is itself.
· Law of Non‑Contradiction:
    \neg(P \land \neg P)
  
    A statement cannot be both true and false at the same time.
· Law of Excluded Middle:
    P \lor \neg P
  
    For any proposition, either it is true or its negation is true.

---

II. The Arithmetic Foundation (Peano Axioms)

· Succession: Every natural number n has a unique successor S(n). This generates the infinite chain of \mathbb{N}.
· Induction: If a property holds for 0 and for S(n) whenever it holds for n, then it holds for all natural numbers.

---

III. The Geometric Foundation (Euclid / Hilbert)

· The Parallel Postulate: Given a line and a point not on it, there is exactly one line through the point that does not intersect the first. (Accepting this creates Euclidean space; denying it creates the curved space of Relativity.)

---

IV. The Set Theoretic Foundation (ZFC — Essence)

· Axiom of Extensionality:
    A = B \iff \forall x (x \in A \iff x \in B)
· Axiom of Infinity: There exists at least one infinite set. (Without this, we cannot have \mathbb{R} or Calculus.)
· Axiom of Choice: Given a collection of non‑empty sets, there exists a choice function selecting exactly one element from each set. (Essential for modern Analysis and Topology.)

---

V. The Meta‑Mathematical Boundary

· Church–Turing Thesis: Anything that is “effectively calculable” can be computed by a Turing machine. This defines the limit of what human (or artificial) intelligence can solve.

